title: Grateful Dead Live at Richmond Coliseum on 1983-10-08
description: Feel Like A Stranger, Friend Of The Devil, Minglewood Blues, Brown Eyed Women, Cassidy, West L.A. Fadeaway, Hell In A Bucket-> Deal Day Job-> Playin' In The Band-> Crazy Fingers-> Drums-> Truckin'-> Spoonful-> Wharf Rat-> Good Lovin', E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: Good Show - 3.5 Stars, Great Audience Sound Quality I give this show 3.5 stars overall, rounding up to 4 because Richmond was one of my favorite places to see shows. It was a cool venue with excellent acoustics, and the free-for-all open floor.  This show was on my birthday, which was always fun.  Energetic Stranger opener, good first set through Cassidy, after that it peters out a little. Second set Playin', Crazy Fingers, Spoonful are all excellent.
James Bond Jam Check out Bobby's James Bond jam during Playing In The Band...cm

Slightly above average for '83 First set is fairly good by '83 standards. Stranger cooks pretty nicely; after that, everything is solid but nothing spectacular and they crank it up a notch for "Deal". The second set started with an almost obligatory (at the time) "Day Job", and then the boys settled down to business And just for the record, while "Day Job" might not have been among the Dead's best songs, it was by no means bad enough to warrant all the abuse it got. It's certainly better than "Easy Answers", "Samba In the Rain" and some of the other utter shit the band was introducing the last couple of years. Anyway, the second set really takes off during the "Playin'" jam and holds at an above average level for the rest of the evening. Great "Sugar Mag" tease before "Good Lovin'". Solid audience recording that holds up to repeated listenings, but nothing essential. I'd recommend this one primarily to fans of early 80s Dead. PS- I have never seen a soundboard of this show.
